Explore global development with R

In this exercise, you will load a filtered gapminder dataset - with a subset of data on global development from 1952 - 2007 in increments of 5 years - to capture the period between the Second World War and the Global Financial Crisis.

Your task: Explore the data and visualise it in both static and animated ways, providing answers and solutions to 7 questions/tasks within this script.

  • Submit to Github this script with solutions and its knitted version.
  • Submit to Brightspace a document with the (1) URL of this script and its knitted version in Github (2) answer of 250 words and a (3) visualisation of the Final Question

The dataset contains information on each country in the sampled year, its continent, life expectancy, population, and GDP per capita.

Letâs plot all the countries in 1952.

theme_set(theme_bw()) 

ggplot(subset(gapminder, year == 1952), aes(gdpPercap, lifeExp, size = pop, color = continent)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +  
  scale_x_log10(labels = label_comma()) + 
  scale_size(labels = label_number(scale_cut = cut_short_scale())) +  
  labs(
    title = "1952",
    x = "BNP pr. indbygger (USD)",  
    y = "Forventet levealder (Ã¥r)",

Som det fremgÃ¥r af ovenstÃ¥ende plot uden log10-skala pÃ¥ x-aksen, bliver det svÃ¦rt at se forskellene mellem lande med en lav BNP pr. indbygger. Det giver derfor mening at bruge en log10-skala pÃ¥ x-aksen (scale_x_log10()) i dette plot, eftersom BNP pr. indbygger varierer kraftigt mellem landene i datasÃ¦ttet. En lineÃ¦r skala betyder, at lande med hÃ¸jt BNP ville skubbe de lavere vÃ¦rdier tÃ¦t sammen, hvilket gÃ¸r det svÃ¦rt at se forskelle i de lavere intervaller. Logaritmisk skalering strÃ¦kker de lavere vÃ¦rdier og komprimerer de hÃ¸jere vÃ¦rdier, sÃ¥ det er muligt at sammenligne lande pÃ¥ tvÃ¦rs af Ã¸konomiske niveauer.

Make it move!

Tasks for the animations:

  1. Can you add a title to one or both of the animations above that will change in sync with the animation? (Hint: search labeling for transition_states() and transition_time() functions respectively)

  2. Can you made the axesâ labels and units more readable? Consider expanding the abbreviated labels as well as the scientific notation in the legend and x axis to whole numbers. Also, differentiate the countries from different continents by color

Jeg har fÃ¥et hjÃ¦lp af chatgpt til at lave nedenstÃ¥ende kode.

anim2 <- ggplot(gapminder, aes(gdpPercap, lifeExp, size = pop, color = continent)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_x_log10(labels = label_comma()) + 
  scale_size(labels = label_number(scale_cut = cut_short_scale())) +  
  labs(title = "Global udvikling i BNP og levealder (Ãr: {frame_time})",  
       x = "BNP pr. indbygger (USD)",
       y = "Forventet levealder (Ã¥r)",  
       size = "Befolkning",  
       color = "Kontinent") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",  
    legend.box = "vertical",  
    legend.spacing.y = unit(0.5, "cm"), 
    legend.text = element_text(size = 10), 
    axis.text = element_text(size = 10)
  ) +
  guides(
    size = guide_legend(title = "Befolkning", order = 1),  
    color = guide_legend(title = "Kontinent", order = 2)  
  ) +
  transition_time(year)

anim2
